source: cli/tests/help.rs
expression: text
---
Delete uuid tree so that kernel can rebuild it at mount time

The UUID tree maps subvolume UUIDs to their root IDs. If it becomes corrupted it
can prevent mount or cause subvolume lookup failures. Deleting it is safe
because the kernel rebuilds it automatically on the next mount.

The device must not be mounted.

Usage: clear-uuid-tree <DEVICE>

Arguments:
  <DEVICE>
          Path to the btrfs device

Options:
  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')
